Cluster Analysis

Clustering Collegiate Womens Basketball Teams

Jade Gosar

2023-11-03

Data Source

The data used for this analysis came from Sports Reference (https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/) which provides game metrics and advanced statistics for multiple collegiate and professional sports teams and leagues. The following cluster models and analysis are based on collegiate womens basketball teams that were in the PAC12 or ended the season ranked in the AP top 25.

Data Cleaning and Manipulation

After getting the Sport Reference stats together for all teams in the top 25 and the PAC 12, I added a column to represent the net ranking which let a strength of schedule metric be incorporated into the cluster analysis that is used by the NCAA to rank teams beyond simply wins and losses. After looking at how the teams compare across the important metrics in the dataset, the decision was made to remove cal and asu as they were not able to be easily grouped with the other teams due to their performance being two of the worst in the PAC12 and having by far the lowest net rankings across the teams.

# Add net rankings

K-means Cluster Analysis

The first clustering approach was to use averages for almost all of the metrics. This cluster analysis will be more complex and includes variables such as pace, 3 point attempt rate, and blocks that were not deemed significant in the logistic regression model on these stats using game outcome as the target variable. The approach will be to compare this analysis to a second model on just the significant predictors to see how much they differ and which captures the data more accurately.

# Create df with averages of almost all metrics
df_for_cluster_analysis2 <- sr_top_teams %>%
  group_by(Team_Name) %>%
  summarize(Number_Of_Wins = sum(`W/L` == "W"),
            Number_Of_Losses = sum(`W/L` == "L"),
            NET_rank = mean(NET_Ranking),
            Avg_Pace = mean(`Pace`),
            Avg_3PAr = mean(`3PAr`),
            Avg_AST_Perc = mean(`AST%`),
            Avg_STL_Perc = mean(`STL%`),
            Avg_BLK = mean(`BLK`),
            Avg_Off_EFG_Perc = mean(`Offensive eFG%`),

## *** : The Hubert index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters.
##                 In the plot of Hubert index, we seek a significant knee that corresponds to a 
##                 significant increase of the value of the measure i.e the significant peak in Hubert
##                 index second differences plot. 
## 

## *** : The D index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters. 
##                 In the plot of D index, we seek a significant knee (the significant peak in Dindex

## 
##                    ***** Conclusion *****                            
##

##  
##

From this analysis we can see how teams in one cluster compare to teams from different clusters across all metrics shown in the visualization above. If we were interested in finding how the first cluster is similar and different to other clusters, we would see that cluster 1 tends to have a slightly lower steal percentage and plays at a faster pace. This group of teams has the lowest offensive rebound percentage by quite a large margin, the highest eFG% allowed by opponents, and performs very well in offensive metrics such as eFG%, assist percentage, and shoots a higher rate of free throws per field goal attempt. Lastly, cluster 1 teams have an average defensive rebound percentage and has a much higher three point attempt rate compared to cluster 2 and 3. Cluster 2 contains many high performing teams, such as LSU, South Carolina, and Stanford, that tend to rely more heavily on defense rather than offense to win games. They have the lowest opponent eFG% by a long shot, shoot a much lower number of threes, and rely heavily on both offensive and defensive rebounding. They also tend to turn the ball over more than clusters 1 and 3, get a much higher number of blocks, and perform about average (fall between the best and worst cluster) across all other metrics. From this model it is clear that teams in cluster 1 rely much more heavily on offensive metrics to win games in which they shoot more 3s and play at a faster pace while teams from cluster 2 tend to rely on playing great defense and getting boards on both ends of the court.

I followed a very similar process to the first cluster analysis below but only used variables that were deemed significant by our logisitic regression on game outcome to compare if creating a cluster model with just these variables better captures the groupings in the data.

g_heat_2

This cluster analysis was different than the last one as it recommended that 4 rather than 3 clusters was the ideal way to split the data set with less variables than the first analysis used. In this cluster model the highest performing teams from the season are in either cluster 2 or cluster 4, with other top 25 teams falling into cluster 1. Similarly to last time, the teams with the best offensive related metrics such as eFG% and a low turnover percentage fall into one cluster (cluster 4) who also draw more fouls. These elite teams allow the highest eFG% by their opponents and tend to struggle on the offensive glass, getting the lowest number of offensive boards compared to the other clusters but an above average number of defensive rebounds. Cluster 2 contains elite defensive teams such as LSU and South Carolina that hold their opponents to a very low shooting percentage and dominate rebounding on both ends of the floor but shoot only slightly above average from the field. Teams such as UCLA, Duke, and Ohio State fall into cluster 1 which is a high performing cluster that is differentiated from the others through a very high steal percentage, a low turnover percentage, and giving up a higher rate of free throws per field goal attempt.

Hierarchical clustering

The next analysis I ran was a hierarchical clustering model. This model is meant to show which teams across the entire data set are most similar and dissimilar from each team and can be used to validate that the clustering analysis is correctly grouping teams together. There are three different types of linkages that you can specify when performing hierarchical clustering which will be bench marked against each other to see which is the most accurate. You can kind of read the diagrams as the lower the branch between the two points, the more similar they are so if the original branch between them is very high up it means they are very dissimilar to each other.

# Add row numbers as a new column and display them next to Team_Name

  rownames_to_column(var = "Row_Num")

# Print the updated data frame

The model that performed the best was the average linkage, shown below. For an example of how to use this model to find teams that are most similar and different, lets look at team 25. In this cluster model the teams that are the most similar to team 25 are Iowa (7), Indiana (6), and Oklahoma (15) and the teams that are the least similar are LSU (8), South Carolina (18), and Stanford (19). This model helps to confirm what we found in the original cluster model which is that these two groups of teams have very different styles of play.

# Create data for hierarchical clustering
d <- dist(cluster_1_w_names[,-c(1, 3)], method = "euclidean")

# Create hierarchical clustering model using average linkage
fit.a <- hclust(d, method="average")
plot(fit.a, main = "Average Linkage", xlab = "Observations", ylab = "Height", cex = .6)

The model below shows the same results as above but performs slightly worse at representing the similarity between the teams.

# Create hierarchical clustering model using ward linkage
fit.w <- hclust(d,method="ward.D2")
plot(fit.w, main = "Ward Linkage", xlab = "Observations", ylab = "Height", cex = .6)

The model below shows that Iowa, Indiana, and UConn (2) are the most similar to team 25 with a couple more teams included in the group that is the most dissimilar, such as Notre Dame (13) and Tenessee (20). This model performs worse than the other two models but still captures the relationships decently well.
